title: Introduction to R ( Part of Beginners R Workshops)
description:
Introduction to R and RStudio

R-Ladies Orlando will be running few sessions for Absolute R Beginners!! There will be a short intro to RStudio and R basics at 7:00, followed by Q&A time. This is an opportunity for anyone completely new to R to get started.

Bring your (charged) laptop and we'll help you get up and running with the software, walk you through the R programming basics, help with FAQs, point you to relevant learning resources, and any other fundamental R questions you may have!

Please make sure you have R and RStudio downloaded ready to go.

To download R, go to https://cloud.r-project.org (https://cloud.r-project.org/)

To download RStudio http://www.rstudio.com/download

Follow the instructions to download and install.

Also please create an account with Kaggle, as we are going to be using a lot of their datasets. I think you can loggin with your gmail, yahoo and even facebook account.

After we get comfortable playing with R and RStudio will start a series of workshops that will be based on Garrett Grolemund and Hadley Wickham book, "R for Data Science" http://r4ds.had.co.nz/

* Visualization: Base R + ggplot

* Introduction to tidyverse

* Data Science with R

-Import

-Tidy

Transform

-Model and Visualize

-Communicate

Everyone is welcome!

title: Launch Meetup
description:
Hello Everyone,

Thanks for joining R-Ladies! We're excited to have you aboard.

Our Launch Meetup will be August 8th, 2017 , 7:00-8:30 PM at the Iron Yard.

This is an opportunity for us to get to know each other, interact and mingle. Every R level is welcome. If you don't know anything about R programming, but have been hearing about data analysis and data science , this is a great way to start. In this meeting we will help you install R, Rstudio and Github, so that you can be ready to tackle the projects and tutorials coming the next meetups.

If you are an R expert, please join our chapter and the launch meeting, as you can help better serve our community by setting goals and priorities for our chapter. All of us, at any level of expertise will help shape the goals and direction of this chapter; so please join us!

We hope this will be a collaborative, supportive space to get to know other folks doing work in R, hear about interesting projects, and find your community and collaborators.

Check out our website (http://rladies.org/) to learn more about R-Ladies and here is our code of conduct (https://github.com/rladies/starter-kit/wiki/Code-of-Conduct)

The tentative agenda includes:

7:00 PM - 7:30 PM - Arrive & Enjoy snacks and drinks

7:30 PM - 8:00 PM - Short presentation & discussion

â€¢ Intro to R-Ladies

â€¢ What is R? why do I need it?

â€¢ Open discussion for future Meetup ideas!

8:00 PM - 8:30 PM - Install R, R Studio and Github.

Please RSVP so that I can plan seating, food and raffle prizes.

Again, thank you for your support and looking forward to meeting you all.

And special thank you to the Iron Yard for giving us a space to use.

Kathy

R-Ladies Orlando

title: Advanced Data Wrangling with dplyr: Part I
description:
Let's move beyond basic skills and dig deeper into more advanced techniques for data wrangling using dplyr. In this session we will learn about: Selecting columns based on partial column names
Selecting columns based on regex
Selecting columns by their data type
Selecting columns by logical expressions

Re-ordering columns:
Column names
Renaming columns
Reformatting all column names
Row names to column

Mutating several columns at once
Mutate_all
Mutate_if
Mutate_at to change specific columns

Working with discrete columns
Recoding discrete columns
Creating new discrete column (two levels)
Creating new discrete column (multiple levels)
Splitting and merging columns
Bringing in columns from other data tables
Spreading and gathering data
Turning data into NA

Thank you Susan Baert from R-Ladies Brussels for creating this tutorial.

â€¢ What to bring
Charged laptop with R, Rstudio and Tidyverse package ready to go.

â€¢ Important to know
You must adhere to our code of conduct. https://github.com/rladies/starter-kit/wiki/Code-of-Conduct

title: Patchwork Orlando (GitHub workshop)
description:
RLadies Orlando and Girls Develop It Orlando are proud to partner with GitHub to bring you hands on workshop for learning Git and GitHub. The event will be open to beginners and mentors who want to help others learn. We will only have 50 seats and we will be opening the event to the Orlando Tech community.
You MUST use this link https://ti.to/github-events/patchwork-orlando-2018 to register for the event. You MUST register through the link to reserve your seat. This is a free event and it will be open to the Orlando tech community.

*GitHub 101: Introduction to GitHub
*GitHub 102: Using the GitHub Desktop
*GitHub 103: Using the Command Line

â€¢ What to bring: your fully charged laptop, and if you do not yet have a GitHub account, we ask that you please signup https://github.com before you attend the event. Its easy , fast and of course free.

title: Women in Data Science @UCF
description:
â€¢ What we'll do
This is a great opportunity to participate and be part of the Data Science community right here in Orlando. The event is FREE and ALL are welcome!

The Global Women in Data Science (WiDS) Conference aims to inspire and educate data scientists worldwide, regardless of gender, and support women in the field. This annual one-day technical conference provides an opportunity to hear about the latest data science related research and applications in a broad set of domains, All genders are invited to participate in the conference, which features exclusively female speakers.

The University of Central Florida's Master of Science in Data Analytics Program is pleased to host this year's program. We will provide a simulcast of the national event from Stanford, as well as the feature the following local speakers:

title: Active Data Analysis
description:
â€¢ What we'll do : "Data doesnâ€™t speak for itself, instead it must be interpreted. This is the process of selecting and obtaining the relevant data, finding the interesting facts or patterns, putting them in context, and explaining what they mean" This meetup will be an 'Active' data analysis session. We will be looking at students' SAT , GPA scores and try to draw conclusion on their college success. Dr. Kari l Jordan will be discussing the meta data and what questions to ask when presented with new dataset. â€¢ What to bring: Charged laptop with R, Rstudio and Tidyverse package ready to go. You can download the dataset before hand here: https://github.com/rladies/meetup-presentations_orlando.git

SampleStudents.csv

If you are new to R programming, this will be a good session to see the thought process that goes into data analysis. We will be offering more "beginner friendly" tutorials in the future, please stay connected!

â€¢ Important to know : As always , everyone is welcome, but must adhere to our code of conduct : https://github.com/rladies/starter-kit/wiki/Code-of-Conduct

TEEPS has graciously offered to host our Meetups and it will be our regular home for the year. They are downtown, but have free parking. (www.teeps.org) Please use door facing colonial drive. There are only 20 parking spot designated to TEEPS, make sure you park there. Also please look at photos for directions and parking info.

title: Start 2018 with a bang!
description:
â€¢ What we'll do
Let's welcome 2018 together.

Join us January 24,2018 to welcome the new year and 2 new community partners: R-Consortium and TEEPS.

TEEPS has graciously offered to host our Meetups and it will be our regular home for the year. They are downtown, but have free parking. (www.teeps.org) We couldn't be more excited to finally have Amanda Cesario presenting at this Meetup. Amanda is a Senior Analyst at EA sports, she will share with us some of her educational background and career path, how she uses R at EA, and give us a glimpse of her everyday tasks and responsibilities. She is a great inspiration to launch this new year and keep us motivated to learn R.

This is a casual meetup where we get the chance to simply socialize and network, so no need to bring your laptop. R-Consortium is kindly sponsoring this event, so we will have food and drinks. If you are new to R , this will be a great introductory meetup so please don't hesitate to attend.

Agenda:
7:00 - 7:30 Food and Drinks
7:30 - 8:00 Amanda Cesario's presentation
8:00 - 8:30 Q&A, chat and socialize.

As always , everyone is welcome, but must adhere to our code of conduct : https://github.com/rladies/starter-kit/wiki/Code-of-Conduct

Looking forward to seeing you soon!

title: R Beginner series: Introduction to dplyr II
description:
New Year / New Skills
Let 2019 be a game changing year for you. Come learn R and Data Science skills with us!!

R-Ladies Orlando will be running few sessions for Absolute R Beginners!! There will be a short intro to RStudio and R basics at 7:00, followed by an intro to R for Data Science, using the tidyverse package, specifically dplyr. This is part 4 of the series, but it is still an opportunity for anyone completely new to R to get started.

Bring your (charged) laptop and we'll help you get up and running with the software, walk you through the R programming basics, help with FAQs, point you to relevant learning resources, and any other fundamental R questions you may have!

Please look over our github page for materials from our last workshop (2019-01-23) and see if you can follow through the examples https://github.com/rladies/meetup-presentations_orlando/tree/master/2019-01-23_Workshop

Please make sure you have R and RStudio downloaded ready to go.

To download R, go to https://cloud.r-project.org (https://cloud.r-project.org/)

To download RStudio http://www.rstudio.com/download

Follow the instructions to download and install.

Also please create an account with Kaggle, as we are going to be using a lot of their datasets. I think you can loggin with your gmail, yahoo and even facebook account.

The beginners series will be based on Garrett Grolemund and Hadley Wickham book, "R for Data Science" http://r4ds.had.co.nz/

Tentative schedule:

* Visualization with ggplot2 (End of February)

* Introduction to tidyverse (End of March)

* Data Science with R (End of April)

-Import

-Tidy

-Transform

-Model and Visualize

-Communicate

â€¢ Important to know
Anyone and everyone interested in R/Data Science should join our group and participate/contribute in any way you can, be they learners, teachers, developers or innovators! We encourage women and minority genders to present/lead most sessions, conversations but we have no restrictions whatsoever when it comes to membership, participation, and discussions. So, please join us and bring your R-family & R-friends!

You must adhere to our code of conduct. https://github.com/rladies/starter-kit/wiki/Code-of-Conduct
